value.value: Dyspnea experienced while at rest.
Dyspnea experienced during minimal exertion.
Dyspnea experienced during moderate exertion.

label.value: Dyspnea with No Physical Activity Limitation

value.value: Dyspnea that does not interfere with their physical activity.
Encephalopathy in a patient with probable or confirmed acute COVID-19.
Addresses geographic variability in medical practice in the United States and the medical and nonmedical factors that create this variability.

Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) in which a venous cannula is typically placed in the right or left common femoral vein for extraction, and an arterial cannula is usually placed into the right or left femoral artery for infusion, with an oxygenator between the extraction and infusion cannulae.

Extracorporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO) to provide adequate gas exchange, usually in respiratory failure/ARDS. The access cannula is usually placed in the inferior vena cava via the femoral vein. The tip of the return cannula is placed close to the right atrium, and it may be placed via the femoral or internal jugular vein.
The presence or absence of symptoms due to acute COVID-19.

label.value: New-onset Heart Failure Associated with Post-Acute Sequelae of SARS-CoV-2 Infection

value.value: New onset of heart failure with a clinical syndrome of dyspnea, fatigue, fluid retention/peripheral edema that started during probable or confirmed acute COVID-19 and persisted beyond four weeks after the initial diagnosis of COVID-19.

label.value: Acute Heart Failure Related to COVID-19

value.value: New or worsening signs of heart failure in a patient with probable or confirmed acute COVID-19. This can be the first presentation or it can reflect an acute decompensation in a patient with history of chronic heart failure.
Admission to a hospital due the health effects caused by COVID-19 infection.

label.value: Hospitalization with Incidental Diagnosis of SARS-CoV-2 Infection

value.value: A hospitalization for a reason not related to COVID-19 infection during which a diagnosis of COVID-19 infection is made.

label.value: Myocardial Edema by T2 Mapping or T2-weighted Imaging

value.value: Regional or global myocardial increase in signal intensity on T2-weighted images suggestive of edema.

label.value: Myocardial Injury by Late Gadolinium Enhancement of T1 Imaging

value.value: Global myocardial increase in signal intensity on gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted images suggestive of myocardial injury.
Regional or global myocardial injury as suggested by T1-weighted images.
Pericardial effusion or thickening as suggested by increased signal intensity or late gadolinium enhancement.
A cardioverter-defibrillator implanted under the skin.
A cardioverter-defibrillator implanted via a central vein.

label.value: Inappropriate Sinus Tachycardia Associated with Post-Acute Sequelae of SARS-CoV-2 Infection

value.value: Inappropriate sinus tachycardia at rest with heart rate  greater than 100 bpm that cannot be explained by any identifiable cause, including anemia, hypoxia, hypotension, or fever that started during probable or confirmed acute COVID-19 and persisted beyond four weeks after the initial diagnosis of COVID-19.
The evaluation of a patient's care with the focus on minimizing their discomfort and maximizing their quality of life rather than curing their disease.
A procedure undertaken to re-establish blood flow through a vessel via introduction of a medical device.
Normal breath sounds noted during auscultation.
Diminished breath sounds noted during auscultation.

A part of a thing, or of several things, taken to demonstrate or to determine the character of the whole, e.g. a substance, or portion of material obtained for use in testing, examination, or study; particularly, a preparation of tissue or bodily fluid taken for examination or diagnosis.
Absence of breath sounds noted during auscultation.

The difference between the mean pulmonary artery pressure and the mean pulmonary capillary wedge pressure.

label.value: Neurovascular Disorder Associated with Post-Acute Sequelae of SARS-CoV-2 Infection

value.value: A disorder of the nervous system related to a vascular etiology that started during probable or confirmed acute COVID-19 and persisted beyond four weeks after the initial diagnosis of COVID-19.
A non-invasive ventilatory treatment that continuously adjusts positive airway pressure (PAP) to prompt breathing when needed based on a patient's breathing pattern.

The oxygen content of the venous blood returned to the heart via the superior and inferior vena caval system after perfusing the entire body.  The venous blood in the pulmonary artery, measured using a pulmonary artery catheter, represents oxygen extraction from the whole body.
The collaboration of two pharmaceutical companies, Pfizer and BioNTech, that together developed COVID-19 mRNA vaccines.
The disposition of a patient to hospice care.
The percent diameter stenosis after the treatment of the lesion.
The percent diameter stenosis immediately before the treatment of the lesion.

A percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) that is performed on an outpatient basis or during a subsequent hospitalization without significant risk of infarction or death. For stable inpatients, the procedure is being performed during their hospitalization for convenience and ease of scheduling but not because the patients clinical situation demands the procedure before discharge. If the diagnostic catheterization was elective and there were no complications, the PCI would also be considered elective.

A percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) that is performed as soon as possible because of substantial concerns that ongoing ischemia or infarction could lead to death. As soon as possible refers to a case of sufficient acuity that a scheduled case would be cancelled to perform this procedure immediately in the next available room during business hours, or the on-call team would be activated if this were to occur during off-hours.

A percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) that is a last resort in a patient with cardiogenic shock when the PCI begins (i.e., at the time of introduction into a coronary artery or bypass graft of the first guidewire or intracoronary device for the purpose of mechanical revascularization). Within the last 10 minutes before the start of the case, or during the diagnostic portion of the case, the patient may have received chest compressions for a total of at least 60 seconds or have been on unanticipated extracorporeal circulatory support (e.g., extracorporeal mechanical oxygenation (ECMO), or cardiopulmonary support).

A percutaneous coronary intervention (PCI) that is performed on an inpatient basis and before discharge because of significant concerns that there is risk of ischemia, infarction, or death. Patients who are outpatients or in the emergency department at the time that the cardiac catheterization is requested would warrant an admission based on their clinical presentation.

label.value: Catheter-based Miniaturized Left Ventricular Assist Device

value.value: A percutaneously implanted miniaturized heart pump.

label.value: Pericardial Effusion Associated with Post-Acute Sequelae of SARS-CoV-2 Infection

value.value: Pericardial effusion that started during probable or confirmed acute COVID-19 and persisted beyond four weeks after the initial diagnosis of COVID-19.
